That sounds like a valid and important primary outcome measure. Do you have any secondary outcome measures in mind as well?

Some ideas for secondary outcome measures could include:

- Number of Hematopoietic Stem Cell Transplantation-Associated Thrombotic Microangiopathy (TMA) events, defined as the occurrence of two or more of the following criteria: thrombocytopenia < 30 x 10^9/L, schistocytes > 2% in the peripheral blood smear, and lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) > 600 U/L;
- Time to TMA onset;
- Days of platelet transfusion (PT) required;
- Days of red blood cell transfusion (RBC) required;
- Total number of transfusions required;
- Number of febrile neutropenia events;
- Length of hospital stay.

These measures would provide additional information on the safety and effectiveness of the Thymoglobulin® dosing regimen being studied.

Remember to also consider feasibility, reliability, and validity when selecting outcome measures. Good luck with your study!
